WEBVTT

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:07.600
Yeah, thanks. I'm here to talk about Shiny. My name is Joe Cheng. I am the CTO of Posit,

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:12.480
which was formerly known as RStudio. And if you have heard of Shiny before,

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:16.879
probably it's in the context of being an R package, and this is not that.

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:23.360
This is Shiny for Python. So just because I know it's come, like, some people have had

00:00:23.360 --> 00:00:29.200
this preconception, what it is not is a Python wrapper around the R version of Shiny. Ugh.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:34.400
Yeah, I wouldn't do that to you. It is a pure Python version of the ideas that are in Shiny.

00:00:35.599 --> 00:00:41.439
This is an example of, like, a very simple Shiny for Python app. And

00:00:43.439 --> 00:00:48.080
this is a simulation of a three-body problem. So you have three bodies in space that are

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:52.880
interacting, Earth, Moon, and Planet X, and you have all different settings for them,

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:58.400
and you can press run simulation, and it will do a simulation using Astropy,

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:02.560
and then draw the results on a matplotlib 3D scatter plot here.

00:01:03.119 --> 00:01:07.120
So I can play with these settings, change the mass of Earth to be

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:11.440
unrealistically low, and run it again and get a different result.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:17.360
So this is a pretty simple... Oh, wow. That's pretty crazy.

00:01:17.919 --> 00:01:20.160
So it's a good thing that's not what Earth weighs.

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:28.480
So that's a super, super simple example, and we'll kind of ramp it up as we go.

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:33.199
Now, about Shiny, Shiny is designed primarily with data scientists in mind,

00:01:34.239 --> 00:01:39.519
and that means that no HTML, CSS, or JavaScript skills are required.

00:01:41.199 --> 00:01:45.360
We also use a very easy-to-use reactive programming model, and I'll talk a little

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:50.320
bit more about what that means. So the goal is to be really approachable

00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:52.720
for people who have a data science background in Python.

00:01:53.839 --> 00:01:58.480
However, I'm not a data scientist. I'm a software engineer.

00:01:58.480 --> 00:02:05.919
I've been doing web development since late 90s, and it would be really frustrating for me

00:02:05.919 --> 00:02:10.800
to work full-time on a web framework that felt very low as common denominator,

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:14.960
or very sort of like a lot of guardrails everywhere.

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:21.199
So if you do know HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, you can fully leverage those skills to customize,

00:02:21.199 --> 00:02:26.320
to extend Shiny, to make your apps more powerful.

00:02:26.320 --> 00:02:30.399
And this same reactive programming model that's easy to get started with

00:02:30.399 --> 00:02:34.000
is also powerful, flexible, and deep.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.520
I mean, I've been programming with this model for 11 years,

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:41.520
and just I am more and more appreciative of what it can do,

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:42.960
and I'll show you some of those things.

00:02:43.919 --> 00:02:49.360
But before we do that, I'm going to show you sort of the high-level anatomy of a Shiny app.

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:54.559
Now, I don't expect you to be able to ingest all that code.

00:02:54.559 --> 00:02:59.520
So for pretty much this whole talk, the goal is not like you don't have to squint

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:02.720
and read every line of code. This is going to be a very kind of lean back

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:07.119
kind of a talk when it comes to the code. So I want to point out here that there are

00:03:07.119 --> 00:03:12.720
just two main pieces to any Shiny app. There's the user interfaces, this first chunk of code,

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:18.399
and what it does is it generates the look and feel of the app and sends that to the browser.

00:03:19.279 --> 00:03:22.880
In this case, there's an input slider and an output plot,

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:24.639
and that's what you see in this little thumbnail.

00:03:25.679 --> 00:03:31.520
So all this is is Python calls that generate HTML.

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:34.880
That's all it is. So you don't need to know the HTML, but that's what it's doing.

00:03:36.399 --> 00:03:39.759
And the second part you need is this server logic.

00:03:39.759 --> 00:03:44.399
This is Python code that runs while the user is interacting with the application.

00:03:44.399 --> 00:03:50.800
So if they move this slider, then this input.n value is going to change

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:52.880
because that input slider, that first argument n.

00:03:54.080 --> 00:04:01.600
So whenever that input.n value changes, because this function called plot has the

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:06.160
decorator on it called render plot, that's a signal to Shiny that you should go ahead

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:10.320
and rerun this plot whenever something changes and automatically keep it up to date.

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:15.119
So you don't have to tell Shiny when to rerender the plot.

00:04:15.119 --> 00:04:18.399
You just use the values that you want, and this is reactive programming.

00:04:18.399 --> 00:04:21.119
Shiny will automatically take care of knowing when to run it.

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:26.079
And then you just have one line to bring these two objects together and make an application.

00:04:26.079 --> 00:04:29.040
So this is probably the simplest Shiny app you'll ever see.

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:32.239
And this is how your workflow will be.

00:04:32.239 --> 00:04:37.839
You're running VS Code, and we have a Shiny for Python VS Code extension.

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:42.559
So you just press this button here, and you can either run or debug the app,

00:04:42.559 --> 00:04:47.359
and it will run the app in this preview panel on the right, right within VS Code.

00:04:47.359 --> 00:04:52.000
You just hit save on the app on your Python file,

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:53.760
and the application will automatically reload.

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:54.959
So it's very quick to iterate.

00:04:56.239 --> 00:05:02.079
Okay, just a couple more things before we launch into some fun demos.

00:05:02.079 --> 00:05:05.440
So here's an example of kind of a bigger app.

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:09.440
So that last one was kind of unrealistically small, so I could fit it all on the screen.

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:13.760
Here's an example of one that I frankly made it a little more complicated than it needs to be.

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:19.519
So this one has some markup, some markdown at the top that you can use to format text.

00:05:19.519 --> 00:05:21.279
This one uses matplotlib again.

00:05:22.079 --> 00:05:27.440
It has an embedded iPy widget that has an interactive map that you can use to show your location.

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:32.799
And what this application does is it uses Astropy to tell you if you're an astronomer

00:05:32.799 --> 00:05:34.799
and you want to look at some object in the night sky,

00:05:34.799 --> 00:05:36.799
you tell it what objects you're interested in looking at,

00:05:37.359 --> 00:05:39.839
where you are on Earth, and what the date is,

00:05:39.839 --> 00:05:44.239
and it'll tell you these are the best times based on your location and time.

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:50.320
And the way this UI code looks,

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:52.720
you have all these different capabilities coming into play.

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:55.600
You can use raw HTML tags like a heading here.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:57.119
You can use markdown.

00:05:57.119 --> 00:05:58.799
You can have a row column layout.

00:05:58.799 --> 00:05:59.920
You can have outputs.

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:03.440
Again, the details are not very important because the thing that I want to point out

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:08.000
is that if we zoom out and kind of like not even being able to read the code,

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.640
but seeing the indentation, there's a shape to it, right?

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:16.480
Like there's two sort of chunks that are part of this UI layout.

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:21.600
And that actually is mirrored or reflected by what our layout looks like

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:22.799
when it renders in the browser.

00:06:22.799 --> 00:06:25.519
So there's two pieces of code and two pieces.

00:06:25.519 --> 00:06:29.600
And for that second one, that body, there's two columns within it.

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:33.119
And the code also has this shape, has this indentation.

00:06:33.119 --> 00:06:35.200
So this is one of the things that I think,

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:37.679
it's like a really beautiful property of Shiny

00:06:37.679 --> 00:06:41.279
that the hierarchy in your UI is reflected

00:06:41.279 --> 00:06:43.279
in the hierarchy of the indentation of your code.

00:06:43.279 --> 00:06:45.519
And as your application gets more and more complicated,

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:50.000
this is a really nice way to be able to figure out the right place in the code

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.720
where you want to make a change or check something out.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:54.720
Okay, so enough talk.

00:06:56.720 --> 00:06:58.399
I have a couple demos that I want to show.

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:02.720
Oh, sorry.

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:04.880
This is the one that I just talked through.

00:07:09.679 --> 00:07:14.559
Here's just an example of a pretty typical metrics dashboard.

00:07:14.559 --> 00:07:18.640
This one is pulling from a live updating database

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:20.720
that's simulating some model scores.

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:23.440
But you could imagine if you work in a corporation

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:25.200
and you have BI dashboards,

00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:27.440
that's one thing that people really like Shiny for.

00:07:28.799 --> 00:07:34.559
But honestly, that is a very important use case of Shiny,

00:07:34.559 --> 00:07:36.399
but I find it not very interesting for talk.

00:07:36.399 --> 00:07:38.320
So that's the last BI dashboard I'm going to show you.

00:07:39.279 --> 00:07:42.320
Here is a bit more of a fun demo

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:48.239
where the visualization you're looking at is Brownian motion.

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:50.799
And this is an example that came from Plotly.

00:07:51.679 --> 00:07:55.519
And Brownian motion is like the motion of a particle on a surface.

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:57.679
And I can press new data here,

00:07:57.679 --> 00:08:00.079
and it'll generate new random traces.

00:08:00.079 --> 00:08:02.559
And some of them are pretty interesting looking.

00:08:02.559 --> 00:08:03.600
But then some of them...

00:08:05.279 --> 00:08:06.160
Some of them...

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:09.760
It never takes this long.

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:10.239
Okay.

00:08:10.239 --> 00:08:12.720
Some of them, it's a little hard to tell what's going on, right?

00:08:12.720 --> 00:08:15.519
Just because of the particular angle that we're looking at.

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:19.279
Now, because this is Plotly,

00:08:19.279 --> 00:08:20.959
you can click and drag and move it around,

00:08:20.959 --> 00:08:22.000
and you can look at it like that.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:23.200
That's just a feature of Plotly.

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:24.320
That's nothing Shiny is doing.

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:26.959
But to make this a little more interesting,

00:08:27.839 --> 00:08:32.400
I am leveraging the Google Media Pipe library

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:34.640
to track the features of my hand.

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:40.159
So using Shiny, I can calculate a normal vector

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:41.760
that's coming out of my palm.

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:44.000
And then I use that to inform the camera angle

00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:46.719
for this widget.

00:08:46.719 --> 00:08:50.000
Now, the reason I think this is interesting and relevant

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.320
is because this smooth tracking button.

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:55.679
So when I came up with this demo,

00:08:55.679 --> 00:08:58.400
I was at home in my living room like,

00:08:58.400 --> 00:08:59.760
oh my gosh, this is so cool.

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:02.080
And my son, who is my oldest,

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:05.119
who is a freshman in college, computer science major,

00:09:05.119 --> 00:09:07.599
his reaction was, why is it so jittery?

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:09.780
Right?

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:12.159
Kids these days.

00:09:14.880 --> 00:09:16.400
And I didn't even notice, but he's right, right?

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:18.880
It's jittery because my hand's a little jittery,

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:19.760
sensors are jittery.

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:21.760
But I thought it was a good question.

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:24.559
After I got over the initial indignation,

00:09:24.559 --> 00:09:26.080
yeah, OK, what can we do about that?

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:31.840
How can we take this very noisy signal

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:32.719
and smooth it out?

00:09:32.719 --> 00:09:33.679
So we tried a couple of things.

00:09:33.679 --> 00:09:36.080
And what ended up working really nicely

00:09:36.719 --> 00:09:39.440
was this approach of just smoothing the data

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:40.799
over the last five samples.

00:09:40.799 --> 00:09:42.080
Instead of showing the latest data,

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:43.599
we show the mean of the last five.

00:09:44.239 --> 00:09:45.440
And I'm not exaggerating.

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:46.799
This took 10 minutes to write.

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:50.080
And what resulted,

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:54.000
that code is not a smoother for this application.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.679
It's a smoother for any reactive signal in Shiny.

00:09:57.679 --> 00:10:00.080
So any data that's coming in fast and noisy,

00:10:01.039 --> 00:10:03.200
the same 10 lines of code that are behind this app

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:05.119
can be used to have the same smoothing effect.

00:10:07.520 --> 00:10:10.000
So that's what I mean when I say that reactivity,

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.719
it's this easy to get started with,

00:10:12.719 --> 00:10:15.200
but it also has these really deep

00:10:15.200 --> 00:10:16.719
and interesting properties about it.

00:10:16.719 --> 00:10:18.239
And to me, that never gets old.

00:10:19.359 --> 00:10:23.440
So when we came out with Shiny for Python,

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.280
a lot of people out there are already using Shiny for R.

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:29.520
So some people had this kind of a reaction.

00:10:33.119 --> 00:10:36.799
And other people said something like this.

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:39.840
But it's just so easy to throw something up

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:41.039
with Streamlet.

00:10:41.039 --> 00:10:43.440
How many people here have heard of Streamlet?

00:10:44.479 --> 00:10:45.679
Okay, plenty of you.

00:10:45.679 --> 00:10:46.179
Okay.

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:48.880
And we've gotten this question a lot

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:50.960
since the introduction of Shiny for Python,

00:10:50.960 --> 00:10:52.080
because Streamlet is,

00:10:53.840 --> 00:10:56.880
as smilodon138 says,

00:10:56.880 --> 00:10:58.320
just so easy, right?

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:00.479
So I wanted to just take a moment

00:11:00.479 --> 00:11:02.640
to unpack this claim a little bit.

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:05.440
And the promise of Streamlet

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:09.599
is that you can start with a normal script.py

00:11:09.599 --> 00:11:12.479
that's just a straight linear set

00:11:12.479 --> 00:11:16.880
of data analysis function calls.

00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:20.239
And with Streamlet, you can take exactly that script,

00:11:20.239 --> 00:11:22.320
sprinkle in a few Streamlet statements,

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:25.039
and boom, you have an interactive application.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.479
And even if you've never seen Shiny before this talk,

00:11:28.479 --> 00:11:30.719
you already know that Shiny doesn't do that, right?

00:11:30.719 --> 00:11:35.520
That Shiny has this form of a UI and a server

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:37.599
and these little functions with decorators.

00:11:37.599 --> 00:11:41.599
It is asking you to pour your code into its form.

00:11:42.559 --> 00:11:47.200
So the way Streamlet is able to do this,

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:48.479
because that's super cool, right?

00:11:48.479 --> 00:11:50.080
Very nice to be able to just take your script

00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:51.520
and sprinkle in some Streamlet.

00:11:51.520 --> 00:11:53.039
And the way they're able to do this is this.

00:11:53.039 --> 00:11:55.039
Streamlet's architecture allows you to write apps

00:11:55.039 --> 00:11:57.039
the same way you write plain Python scripts.

00:11:57.039 --> 00:12:00.400
To unlock this, Streamlet apps have a unique data flow.

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:02.640
Anytime something must be updated on the screen,

00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:04.880
Streamlet reruns your entire Python script

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:05.840
from top to bottom.

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:06.640
Nobody else does this.

00:12:06.640 --> 00:12:08.239
This is only Streamlet.

00:12:09.760 --> 00:12:12.640
And it really is that easy.

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:13.359
It is true.

00:12:13.359 --> 00:12:16.320
I'm not here to debunk Streamlet's ease of use.

00:12:16.320 --> 00:12:19.119
It is like you might learn Streamlet by accident.

00:12:21.039 --> 00:12:23.919
You could write a Streamlet app falling out of bed.

00:12:23.919 --> 00:12:24.880
It's that easy.

00:12:26.159 --> 00:12:29.359
Now, granted, it's running the entire script

00:12:29.359 --> 00:12:31.359
every time you move a slider,

00:12:31.359 --> 00:12:32.880
every time you click a button.

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:35.119
So as a result, by default,

00:12:35.119 --> 00:12:36.719
it does have slow performance.

00:12:36.719 --> 00:12:39.679
And there's only so much control you can have

00:12:39.679 --> 00:12:41.200
when it's running the entire script

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:42.640
every time anything changes.

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:44.239
You can't opt out of that behavior.

00:12:44.799 --> 00:12:47.280
So that means as your Streamlet apps

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:49.679
get just a little bit more complicated,

00:12:49.679 --> 00:12:52.080
you are actually left in quite a bad place.

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:53.919
So they have introduced some features

00:12:53.919 --> 00:12:56.159
like caching callbacks and session state

00:12:56.159 --> 00:12:59.520
that are designed to let you work around

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:01.280
the top-to-bottom execution model.

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:05.359
So I can very much endorse Streamlet for simple apps.

00:13:05.359 --> 00:13:07.919
And I think they made some really fantastic,

00:13:07.919 --> 00:13:09.039
interesting choices.

00:13:09.039 --> 00:13:10.479
But for the complicated apps,

00:13:11.039 --> 00:13:14.159
you're putting yourself and your users in danger

00:13:14.159 --> 00:13:15.599
because it is very tricky to get

00:13:15.599 --> 00:13:17.280
that kind of application correct.

00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:21.200
So in contrast, Shiny is easy,

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:23.119
though not as easy as Streamlet.

00:13:23.919 --> 00:13:25.039
But it is scalable.

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:29.919
And the history of Shiny is a history of people

00:13:29.919 --> 00:13:32.320
getting so much value out of this framework

00:13:32.880 --> 00:13:34.320
without being web developers,

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:38.239
but building sometimes quite complex apps

00:13:38.239 --> 00:13:42.239
and getting huge results from those apps.

00:13:42.239 --> 00:13:44.320
And the kinds of stories I could tell you

00:13:44.960 --> 00:13:46.799
about the kinds of accomplishments

00:13:46.799 --> 00:13:48.000
people have made on their Shiny apps

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:49.679
would, you know, gives me goosebumps

00:13:49.679 --> 00:13:50.880
just thinking about it.

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:53.280
So I would sum it up by saying

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:56.000
the meantime from getting started

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.280
to having something of value,

00:13:58.159 --> 00:14:00.559
it's Streamlet, it's incredible.

00:14:00.559 --> 00:14:03.359
Like within 10 seconds, you have an interactive plot.

00:14:03.359 --> 00:14:05.840
And with Shiny, maybe it takes you 60 seconds, okay?

00:14:07.679 --> 00:14:11.039
But the meantime before you need to throw that app away,

00:14:11.919 --> 00:14:14.159
in Streamlet, even people who love Streamlet

00:14:14.159 --> 00:14:18.400
will generally agree that

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:19.760
when you write a Streamlet app,

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:21.520
you know you're writing a proof of concept.

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:23.599
And that there is going to be,

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:27.039
like some other team is going to have to rewrite it

00:14:27.039 --> 00:14:29.119
in something else for production.

00:14:29.679 --> 00:14:31.039
And Shiny's not like that.

00:14:31.039 --> 00:14:34.479
Like you don't go into Shiny expecting to throw it away.

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:39.599
Okay, I can't back this up.

00:14:39.599 --> 00:14:40.640
Like these are my feelings.

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:42.960
I am trying to be unbiased here,

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:43.840
but I don't have data.

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:46.640
But this is how I genuinely feel about this.

00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:52.159
Now, until this talk,

00:14:53.200 --> 00:14:54.320
I would just leave it at that

00:14:54.320 --> 00:14:56.080
and say like Streamlet's easier.

00:14:57.039 --> 00:15:00.479
But this talk is actually a little different.

00:15:00.479 --> 00:15:02.080
So a couple of weeks ago,

00:15:03.919 --> 00:15:07.039
my team and I, we sort of challenged ourselves

00:15:07.039 --> 00:15:08.880
to think like, could we close this gap?

00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:11.520
Like, are we okay letting Streamlet

00:15:11.520 --> 00:15:13.359
be so much easier than Shiny?

00:15:13.359 --> 00:15:15.840
And initially, like I was like, yeah, I'm fine with that.

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:17.919
Like they have made some choices

00:15:17.919 --> 00:15:21.599
that are, they're quite severe trade-offs.

00:15:21.599 --> 00:15:23.280
And I'm happy with the trade-offs we've made.

00:15:23.280 --> 00:15:26.080
Until I heard several people tell me

00:15:26.080 --> 00:15:28.640
that they use Streamlet not just to build applications,

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:31.919
but to do exploratory data analysis.

00:15:31.919 --> 00:15:33.679
And that was surprising to me.

00:15:33.679 --> 00:15:35.520
Like this is, that's how easy it is

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:39.599
that they'd rather do these Streamlet interactions

00:15:39.599 --> 00:15:41.359
than stay in their notebook.

00:15:42.239 --> 00:15:45.280
And I was like, oh, that's actually pretty cool.

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:47.760
Like 10 seconds versus 60 seconds.

00:15:47.760 --> 00:15:49.919
That's a big difference if you're doing EDA, right?

00:15:50.799 --> 00:15:53.039
So the question we posed to ourselves

00:15:53.039 --> 00:15:55.679
is can we close this gap without sacrificing this?

00:15:55.679 --> 00:15:59.440
Like, can we make it as easy as Streamlet,

00:15:59.440 --> 00:16:03.919
easy enough to do EDA without forcing you

00:16:03.919 --> 00:16:05.679
to throw away your Shiny app?

00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:10.960
So I have been working my butt off

00:16:10.960 --> 00:16:12.000
for the last two weeks,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:13.520
getting this demo ready for you all.

00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:15.919
But it is highly experimental.

00:16:15.919 --> 00:16:17.919
So I really hate doing demos

00:16:17.919 --> 00:16:20.080
and then not having a pip install at the end.

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:21.359
But this is one of those times

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:23.760
where I was too excited not to show it to you,

00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:25.200
but there's also no call to action

00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:27.760
because this is, I just barely got this working

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:29.119
like two days ago.

00:16:29.119 --> 00:16:33.440
So what I'm going to show you

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:36.400
is a new way of using Shiny.

00:16:40.880 --> 00:16:43.039
And it is inside the Jupyter notebook.

00:16:43.039 --> 00:16:46.960
So Shiny has never been compatible with Jupyter.

00:16:46.960 --> 00:16:49.200
And well, you'll see in a second.

00:16:49.200 --> 00:16:53.119
So let's start out with just loading some data.

00:16:53.119 --> 00:16:55.679
I'm loading the Palmer Penguins dataset here.

00:16:57.679 --> 00:17:01.119
And I'm just going to show,

00:17:01.119 --> 00:17:03.119
there's some columns here.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:09.920
And then I'll do like a simple seaborne scatterplot.

00:17:09.920 --> 00:17:10.420
Okay.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
This is very, this is a very small screen.

00:17:16.560 --> 00:17:17.359
Okay. Can you see it?

00:17:17.359 --> 00:17:18.479
Can you see that okay?

00:17:18.479 --> 00:17:19.199
Yeah. Okay.

00:17:20.959 --> 00:17:23.920
So you know what?

00:17:23.920 --> 00:17:25.119
Since I have a little extra time,

00:17:25.119 --> 00:17:27.599
I'm just going to see if I can live code this.

00:17:29.199 --> 00:17:31.199
So yeah.

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:38.560
Okay.

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:44.640
So the first thing I'm going to do is load Shiny notebook.

00:17:45.599 --> 00:17:53.199
And then I'm going to load some from Shiny import,

00:17:53.199 --> 00:17:54.400
some classes I'll need.

00:18:05.599 --> 00:18:08.640
This one, I really got a kick out of calling a package

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:09.680
Shiny notebook magic.

00:18:12.479 --> 00:18:13.119
So there you go.

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:14.479
Okay.

00:18:14.560 --> 00:18:17.920
So the first thing that we'll do is let's add some inputs.

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:20.160
Okay. So I have the scatterplot here.

00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:23.199
I'd really like to be able to experiment

00:18:23.199 --> 00:18:24.719
with different columns here.

00:18:26.160 --> 00:18:32.560
Like, you know, let's see like what these look like.

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:34.079
And I want to do this interactively

00:18:34.079 --> 00:18:36.560
instead of having to change the code and rerun the cells.

00:18:37.199 --> 00:18:38.719
So what do I need?

00:18:38.719 --> 00:18:42.000
I'll need an X, Y, and Q argument

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.640
that are all columns from this dataset.

00:18:45.439 --> 00:18:50.719
So sorry, I'm not used to working on a screen this small

00:18:50.719 --> 00:18:52.160
and it's screwing up my scrolling.

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:54.239
Okay.

00:18:54.239 --> 00:18:58.319
So in an effort to make this as simple as possible,

00:18:58.959 --> 00:19:01.359
I created a new function called magic inputs.

00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:03.760
And we want X.

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:06.959
And that's going to be one of these call names

00:19:06.959 --> 00:19:07.839
that I saved up here.

00:19:09.599 --> 00:19:10.959
And Y is going to be the same.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:13.599
And actually color is going to be the same.

00:19:13.599 --> 00:19:14.479
These are all going to be the same.

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:17.760
Okay.

00:19:17.760 --> 00:19:20.000
So I have three widgets now.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:21.520
Species, species, species.

00:19:22.479 --> 00:19:24.400
And I can choose any of these columns.

00:19:25.760 --> 00:19:35.359
So the way I use this is I can say input.X and it's species.

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:40.400
And if I change this, it doesn't automatically update.

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:41.680
I have to hit control enter again,

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:43.439
but it's reflecting the newest value.

00:19:43.439 --> 00:19:43.760
Okay.

00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:49.199
So let's now change this code.

00:19:51.359 --> 00:19:52.239
Input.X.

00:19:56.400 --> 00:19:57.199
Input.Y.

00:20:02.079 --> 00:20:03.280
Input.Color.

00:20:04.239 --> 00:20:05.359
And go ahead and run that.

00:20:05.359 --> 00:20:06.000
Okay.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.959
So that is the least interesting plot we could come up with.

00:20:08.959 --> 00:20:15.520
But if I change this and then rerun this, that looks good.

00:20:16.160 --> 00:20:16.400
Okay.

00:20:18.640 --> 00:20:20.160
Let's actually make this react.

00:20:21.280 --> 00:20:22.319
So we're going to do...

00:20:24.079 --> 00:20:26.400
We don't just want to execute this once, right?

00:20:26.400 --> 00:20:28.319
When I run this cell, I want to tell Shiny,

00:20:28.319 --> 00:20:32.239
execute this however many times you need to to keep it up to date.

00:20:32.239 --> 00:20:34.400
So number one, we'll put it into a function.

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:39.359
Because in Python, that's how you package up code.

00:20:39.359 --> 00:20:41.040
And then I say render.plot.

00:20:41.040 --> 00:20:42.719
This is Shiny's render plot function.

00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:46.319
So when I run this, this is now live.

00:20:46.959 --> 00:20:51.040
So I can change this to sex and it instantly updates.

00:20:52.959 --> 00:20:53.280
Okay.

00:20:55.680 --> 00:20:57.199
Now, this is really annoying, right?

00:20:57.199 --> 00:20:58.079
Like, this scrolling.

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:01.040
Because the notebook is linear.

00:21:01.040 --> 00:21:03.280
And especially if I add in, like...

00:21:04.319 --> 00:21:10.239
If I add in, like, df input.x, input.y.

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:15.439
And then actually, let's render this also as a...

00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:26.319
So I'm going to make this live as well.

00:21:27.680 --> 00:21:29.920
So this says build length and build depth.

00:21:29.920 --> 00:21:35.040
But if I change this, this updates.

00:21:35.839 --> 00:21:36.160
Okay.

00:21:36.160 --> 00:21:38.319
So this bothered me enough on Friday.

00:21:38.319 --> 00:21:40.959
All this scrolling around that I added kind of a...

00:21:43.280 --> 00:21:43.599
Okay.

00:21:43.599 --> 00:21:45.920
If you triple click, then you can detach it.

00:21:48.640 --> 00:21:50.319
And then now I can have these things side by side.

00:21:53.040 --> 00:21:55.599
And then when I'm done, I can click this and it goes back away.

00:21:56.880 --> 00:21:57.359
Okay.

00:21:57.359 --> 00:22:02.400
So that, I think, is sort of the EDA side of the equation.

00:22:02.400 --> 00:22:02.719
All right?

00:22:02.719 --> 00:22:04.160
Like, you're screwing around in a notebook.

00:22:04.160 --> 00:22:07.359
You see something and it's starting to get a little bit tedious.

00:22:07.359 --> 00:22:09.359
Flipping back and forth between different values.

00:22:10.640 --> 00:22:15.599
Load up shiny.notebook and add a couple of decorations and you're all set.

00:22:16.959 --> 00:22:19.920
And I'm not going to attempt to live code this one.

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:23.359
But this is that same set of things that I created.

00:22:23.359 --> 00:22:28.800
Except I can also have relationships between the different outputs.

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:28.959
So...

00:22:33.119 --> 00:22:35.280
Again, I'll select some interesting values here.

00:22:38.160 --> 00:22:38.400
And...

00:22:41.359 --> 00:22:41.920
Oh, no!

00:22:45.680 --> 00:22:46.000
Why?

00:22:50.560 --> 00:22:50.800
Oh.

00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:52.319
That's why.

00:22:54.319 --> 00:22:59.439
I regret my decision to do this live.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:02.400
Okay.

00:23:02.400 --> 00:23:03.280
Let's try this again.

00:23:06.959 --> 00:23:07.520
All right.

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:09.199
So in this case...

00:23:11.199 --> 00:23:13.839
There's some interesting values out here.

00:23:13.839 --> 00:23:14.079
Right?

00:23:14.079 --> 00:23:14.959
Like, what are those?

00:23:16.239 --> 00:23:16.479
So...

00:23:19.119 --> 00:23:20.319
I can select them.

00:23:21.280 --> 00:23:26.560
And this data frame will show whatever I have selected.

00:23:27.760 --> 00:23:27.920
Right?

00:23:30.719 --> 00:23:35.599
And an interesting consequence of running this in a notebook and not just in, like,

00:23:35.599 --> 00:23:42.560
a .py file is that I'm also interactively writing code inside of this same Python process.

00:23:42.560 --> 00:23:46.400
This is not something that you could ever do before with Shiny for Python.

00:23:46.400 --> 00:23:47.040
But I can do it now.

00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:53.839
So not only can I have these two selected things reflected here, but I could even...

00:23:59.040 --> 00:24:01.439
I can grab them with code.

00:24:03.839 --> 00:24:10.880
So now if I execute this, I have this outliers variable that has the thing that I brushed.

00:24:10.880 --> 00:24:14.959
And I can go do whatever else I want in this notebook with it.

00:24:14.959 --> 00:24:21.280
So this is stuff that has existed for, like, 48 hours.

00:24:21.280 --> 00:24:25.920
So I don't even know what else this is going to be useful for or when it's going to ship.

00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:33.359
But I will tell you that I think opening that door for ourselves and being willing

00:24:33.359 --> 00:24:38.880
to revisit sort of the assumptions of how and where Shiny should be useful has been really

00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:39.439
exciting.

00:24:39.439 --> 00:24:43.439
I'm actually only showing one of three different things that have come out of this effort from

00:24:43.439 --> 00:24:44.239
the last couple of weeks.

00:24:44.239 --> 00:24:47.680
But it will be for other people to share those other things.

00:24:47.680 --> 00:24:51.119
So that's Shiny for Python.

00:24:51.119 --> 00:24:54.479
If you want to take a look, you can use that QR code.

00:24:54.479 --> 00:24:56.160
And there's a full tutorial.

00:24:56.160 --> 00:24:57.119
There are articles.

00:24:57.119 --> 00:24:59.760
There's lots of examples and documentation.

00:25:00.719 --> 00:25:04.800
And thank you.

